# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The goal is to calculate the probability that Alice has n or fewer points. To achieve this, we can consider the probability at each point and use dynamic programming to build up the probabilities iteratively.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. First, we handle the base cases. If k is 0 or if n is greater than or equal to k + maxPts, Alice will always stop drawing after the first round and have a probability of 1.0 to have n or fewer points.
1. We create an array dp to store the probabilities for each possible number of points.
1. Initialize dp[0] to 1.0, indicating that Alice starts with 0 points.
1. We use a sliding window approach to calculate the probabilities iteratively. We maintain a windowSum variable that represents the sum of probabilities within the window of size maxPts.
1. Iterate from 1 to n and calculate dp[i] as windowSum / maxPts since each draw has equal probabilities.
1. If i is less than k, we update windowSum by adding dp[i] since we can continue drawing.
1. Otherwise, if i is greater than or equal to k, we update probability by adding dp[i] since Alice has stopped drawing at this point.
1. We adjust the windowSum by subtracting the probability that falls outside the window, i.e., dp[i - maxPts], if it exists.
1. Finally, we return the calculated probability.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the solution is O(n) because we iterate from 1 to n to calculate the probabilities.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(n) because we use an array dp of size n+1 to store the probabilities.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public double new21Game(int n, int k, int maxPts) {
        if (k == 0 || n >= k + maxPts)
        return 1.0;

    double[] dp = new double[n + 1];
    double windowSum = 1.0;
    double probability = 0.0;

    dp[0] = 1.0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        dp[i] = windowSum / maxPts;

        if (i < k)
            windowSum += dp[i];
        else
            probability += dp[i];

        if (i - maxPts >= 0)
            windowSum -= dp[i - maxPts];
    }

    return probability;
    }
}
