# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To calculate the trapped rainwater, we need to determine the effective height at each bar. The effective height at a specific bar is the minimum of the maximum heights on its left and right sides. The trapped rainwater can be calculated as the difference between the effective height and the actual height of each bar.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Check if the height array is null or has fewer than 2 elements. If so, return 0 since there are not enough bars to trap any rainwater.
2. Initialize a variable result to keep track of the total trapped rainwater.
3. Create two arrays, left and right, each with the same length as the height array. These arrays will store the maximum heights on the left and right sides of each bar, respectively.
4. Scan the height array from left to right:
- Initialize a variable max to store the maximum height encountered so far, starting with the height of the first bar.
- For each bar at index i, compare its height with the current max:
1. If the height of the current bar is less than the current max, set left[i] to max, indicating that the maximum height on the left side is still max.
1. Otherwise, update left[i] and max to the height of the current bar since it becomes the new maximum height encountered so far.
5. Scan the height array from right to left (similar to step 4) to populate the right array with the maximum heights on the right side of each bar.
6. Iterate over the height array:
- For each bar at index i, calculate the trapped rainwater by subtracting the actual height (height[i]) from the minimum of the maximum heights on the left and right sides (Math.min(left[i], right[i])).
- Add the calculated trapped rainwater to the result variable.
7. Return the final result which represents the total trapped rainwater.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the code is O(n), where n is the length of the height array. The code performs three separate scans over the height array, each taking linear time. Hence, the overall time complexity is linear.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of the code is O(n), where n is the length of the height array. This is due to the additional arrays left and right that store the maximum heights on the left and right sides of each bar, respectively. The space required is proportional to the size of the input array.

# Code
```
class Solution 
{
    public int trap(int[] height) 
    {
        int result = 0;
        if(height==null || height.length<=2)
            return result;
        int left[] = new int[height.length];
        int right[]= new int[height.length];
        //scan from left to right
        int max = height[0];
        left[0] = height[0];
        for(int i=1; i<height.length; i++)
        {
            if(height[i]<max)
            {
                left[i]=max;
            }
            else
            {
                left[i]=height[i];
                max = height[i];
            }
        }
        //scan from right to left
        max = height[height.length-1];
        right[height.length-1]=height[height.length-1];
        for(int i=height.length-2; i>=0; i--)
        {
            if(height[i]<max)
            {
                right[i]=max;  
            }
            else
            {  
                right[i]=height[i];
                max = height[i];
            }
        }

        for(int i=0; i<height.length; i++)
        {
            result+= Math.min(left[i],right[i])-height[i];
        }
        return result;
    }
}
