class Solution {
    public int minSwaps(String s) {
        return util1(s);
    }
    public int util1(String str) {
        Stack<Character> s = new Stack<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            if (str.charAt(i) == '[') {
                s.push(str.charAt(i));
            } else {
                if (s.isEmpty() == false && s.peek() == '[') {
                    s.pop();
                } else {
                    s.push(str.charAt(i));
                }
            }
        }
        double pairs = s.size() / 2;
        double a = pairs / 2.0;
        int ans = (int) Math.ceil(a);
        return ans;
    }
}

content:
the trick behind is fairly easy

for the number of pairs which are not correct, the amount of swaps required to make them correct is Math.ceil(a), where a is the number of pairs which are not correct.

for eg
for 5 incorrect pairs, we need 3 swaps
for 3 incorrect pairs, we need 2 swaps
for 2 incorrect pairs, we need 1 swap

so simply, 
we need to firstly write code to remove all the valid pairs, that ways only the pairs which are incorrect will be in the stack
then we simply do the calculations.

rest the code should be self explanatory.

